{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"25d603d5-c7b1-4914-8fd3-a8e74bdaeb43","content":"## Diagnosis\n\n**.NET MAUI Android doesn't use your system JDK.** It ships its own **Microsoft OpenJDK 17** via the Android workload. When `JAVA_HOME` points to Adoptium Temurin, it overrides the expected JDK and breaks the build toolchain (Gradle, `aapt2`, d8, etc. expect the workload-bundled JDK).\n\n## Fix\n\n**Option 1 — Unset the override** (recommended):\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\n```\n\nRemove any `export JAVA_HOME=…` line from your `~/.zshrc` / `~/.bash_profile` so MAUI auto-discovers its bundled JDK.\n\n**Option 2 — Point to the workload JDK:**\n\n```bash\n# Find the workload-installed JDK:\nls /Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/ | grep microsoft\n\n# Then set JAVA_HOME to it, e.g.:\nexport JAVA_HOME=\"/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home\"\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Pin it in your `.csproj`:**\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nAfter fixing, do a clean rebuild: `dotnet clean && dotnet build -t:Run -f net9.0-android`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"569724a7-904c-41a9-8ade-4f0ca4be4c6b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what common issues exist with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java.\n\nThe key issue here is likely related to .NET MAUI's Java version requirements. Let me check what I know:\n\n- .NET 8 MAUI requires JDK 17\n- .NET 9 MAUI requires JDK 17\n- However, there's a known issue where .NET MAUI (particularly newer versions) requires the **Microsoft OpenJDK** distribution specifically, not just any JDK 17.\n\n\n- The most common culprit is that while they have the right JDK version, it's the wrong distribution—.NET MAUI's Android workload installs Microsoft's OpenJDK and expects JAVA_HOME to point to that specific distribution, not Adoptium Temurin.\n- When JAVA_HOME is set to a different JDK, it bypasses the workload's managed JDK and causes compatibility issues with Gradle and the build tools.\n- The specific errors they're likely hitting are things like `UnsupportedClassVersionError`, Gradle daemon failures, or `Could not determine java version` because the build system is trying to use the wrong JDK entirely.\n- The solution is either unsetting JAVA_HOME entirely to let MAUI use its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK, pointing JAVA_HOME to the Microsoft OpenJDK that came with the workload, or explicitly setting `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the project file.\n- I should also check whether they're on .NET 9, which might have different JDK requirements—though JDK 17 is typically the baseline for Android builds, some newer versions might expect JDK 21. The most likely culprit is that MAUI's bundled Microsoft OpenJDK conflicts with the Adoptium Temurin installation when `JAVA_HOME` is set. I should suggest unsetting `JAVA_HOME` to let MAUI use its own JDK, or alternatively pointing it to the Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the Android workload. mismatch between the JDK versions that different parts of the build system are using. I should focus on the most straightforward explanation and solution for this issue.","outputTokens":1751,"requestId":"1034:E663:155434F:17EAE5D:69FD3401"},"id":"eb95be09-886a-4ab1-9cbd-3590e07281e0","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:54:00.086Z","parentId":"430c7373-525c-4f70-8b95-e373decb1ea2"}
